\begin_layout Title
Spline mimimizing rotation-invariant semi-norms in Sobolev spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jean Duchon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
Université Scientifique et Médicale, Laboratoire de Mathématiques Appliquées,
 B.P.
 53, 38041, Grenoble, France
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We define a family of semi-norms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{m,s}=\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|\mathfrak{F}D^{m}u(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Minimizing such semi-norms, siubject to some interpolating conditions,
 leads to function of very simple forms, providing interpolation methods
 that: 1) preserve polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq m-1$
\end_inset

; 2) commute with similarities as well as translations and rotations of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

; and 3) converge in Sobolev spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{m+s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Typical examples of such splines are: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thin plate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 functions (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a\in A}\lambda_{a}\left|t-a\right|^{2}\log\left|t-a\right|+\alpha t+\beta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}a=0$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multi-conic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 functions (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}\left|t-a\right|+C$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}=0$
\end_inset

), pseudo-cubic splines (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}\left|t-a\right|^{3}+\alpha t+\beta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\lambda_{a}a=0$
\end_inset

), as well as usual polynomial splines in one dimension.
 In general, data functional are only supposed to be distributions with
 compact supports, belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-m-s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

; there may be infinitely many of them.
 Splines are then expressed as convolutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\varodot\left|t\right|^{2m+2s-n}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\varodot\left|t\right|^{2m+2s-n}\log\left|t\right|$
\end_inset

) + polynomials.
\end_layout

