\begin_layout Subsection
Sobolev spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{loc}^{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{comp}^{-s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any real 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is the set of tempered distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}$
\end_inset

 is a (locally summable) function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{s}\left|\hat{u}(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In other words 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}=\mathfrak{F}\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{-s/2}L^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It is a Hilbert space.
 Its dual is naturally identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})=\left\{ u\in L^{2}(\mathbb{R}^{n});D^{\alpha}u\in L^{2}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),\forall\left|\alpha\right|\leq s\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{K}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is the set of distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\in H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 whose support is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{K}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is a closed linear subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 is the set of restrictions, to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, of distributions
\begin_inset Formula $\in H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 It is isomorphic to the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})/H_{\Omega^{c}}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 hence a Hilbert space too.
 Its dual is naturally identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\bar{\Omega}}^{-s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is bounded and sufficiently regular (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 satisfies some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniform cone
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 condition) then (for non integer 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 is the set of distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 whose derivatives of order 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]$
\end_inset

 (integralpart of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

) are in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iint_{\Omega\times\Omega}\frac{\left|D^{\left[s\right]}u(t)-D^{\left[s\right]}u(t^{\prime})\right|^{2}}{\left|t-t^{\prime}\right|^{n+2(s-\left[s\right])}}dtdt^{\prime}<\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For integer 
\begin_inset Formula $s\geq0$
\end_inset

 it suffices that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{\alpha}u\in L^{2}(\Omega),\forall\left|\alpha\right|=s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{loc}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is the set of distributiorson 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose restriction to any bounded open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Of course 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}\subset H_{loc}^{s}$
\end_inset

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq s$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, Sobolev embedding theorems assert that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{loc}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\subset C^{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>k+\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $H_{loc}^{s}$
\end_inset

 may be equipped with a Fréchet space structure: putting 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{N}=$
\end_inset

 the open ball 
\begin_inset Formula ${\left|t\right|<N}$
\end_inset

, one defines a countable family of semi-norms 
\begin_inset Formula $u\mapsto$
\end_inset

 norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{|B_{N}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(B_{N})$
\end_inset

.
 It is reflexive, and its dual is naturally identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{comp}^{-s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, the union of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\bar{B}_{N}}^{-s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, equipped with the topology of (strict) inductive limit of this countable
 family of Hilbert spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All previous norms could have been replaced by equivalent ones, they do
 not play a role by themselves in our problem.
 We now come to definig spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 ,whose semi-norms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert .\right\Vert _{m,s}$
\end_inset

 are fundamental.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We put 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})=\left\{ u\in\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}(\mathbb{R}^{n});\hat{u}\in L_{loc}^{1},\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|\hat{u}(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau<\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We equip it with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{0,s}=\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|\hat{u}(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

}.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
is a Hilbert space
\shape default
 if (and only if) 
\begin_inset Formula $s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

: for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{-s}f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is locally summable, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{K}\left|\tau\right|^{-s}\left|f(\tau)\right|d\tau\leq\left(\int_{K}\left|\tau\right|^{-2s}\right)^{1/2}\left(\int_{K}\left|f(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is locally sunnmble if (and only if) 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>-n$
\end_inset

; therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{-s}f$
\end_inset

 defines a distribution, easily seen to be tempered, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto\mathfrak{F}\left(\left|\tau\right|^{-s}f\right)$
\end_inset

 is an isometry from 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

, one can prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{-s}f_{j}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 (it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left|\tau\right|^{-s}f_{j}\left(\tau\right)\varphi\left(\tau\right)d\tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 rapidly decreasing at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

).
 This implies that inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}\curvearrowleft\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 (a fortiori 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}\curvearrowleft\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

) is continuous, or that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
is a Hilbert subspace of
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We might even prove that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{n}{2}<s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\shape italic
normal
\shape default
 subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{I}$
\end_inset

 as a dense subspace) with dual 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Some of these spaces are known and used in other fields.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{-1}\left(\mathbb{R}^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{1}\left(\mathbb{R}^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 are respectively spaces of charges and potentials of finite energy, in
 the theory of Newtonian potentials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 See 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[10], §11
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From definitions, it is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\subset\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

, the converse if 
\begin_inset Formula $s<0$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{o}=H^{o}=L^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 In general 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\neq\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}\subset L^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 But (at least for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{n}{2}<s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

) 
\shape italic
equality holds on bounded subsets, as we now see
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)=\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{n}{2}<s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 is the set of restrictions, to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 (bounded), of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, with corresponding Hilbert structure.
 In fact, we can prove that any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

) is sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We first note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\leq\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{s}\leq2\left|\tau\right|^{2s}$
\end_inset

 except for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in$
\end_inset

 some ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Now for 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}$
\end_inset

 is a function.
 We write it as 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}+v_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 coincides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}$
\end_inset

 a.e.
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and is zero outside, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{s}\left|v_{1}\left(\tau\right)\right|^{2}d\tau=\int_{B^{C}}\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{s}\left|v_{1}\left(\tau\right)\right|^{2}d\tau\leq\int_{B^{C}}\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|v_{1}\left(\tau\right)\right|^{2}d\tau<\infty$
\end_inset

, so that its inverse Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in H^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 has compact support, hence its (inverse) Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function (in fact, an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

entire function of exponential type
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}\in L^{1}$
\end_inset

).
 Case 
\begin_inset Formula $s<0$
\end_inset

 is exactly similar: we prove 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}\subset\tilde{H}^{s}+C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}\subset H_{loc}^{s}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)=H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $s<0$
\end_inset

 we must prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}\subset\tilde{H}_{loc}^{s}$
\end_inset

; 
\shape italic
but for
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $s>\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}\subset\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

, which gives the result.
 So in general 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)=H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 bounded, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{n}{2}<s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)\curvearrowleft\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)\curvearrowleft H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s<0$
\end_inset

) is continuous, so that the two Hilbert structures induced on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}(\Omega)=H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 are comparable, hence equivalent, from one of Banach's theorems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Semi-Hilbert spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We put 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}=\left\{ u\in\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}(\mathbb{R}^{n});D^{\alpha}u\in\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),\forall\left|\alpha\right|=m\right\} $
\end_inset

, equipped with natural semi-norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{m,s}=\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|\mathfrak{F}D^{m}u(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 We also consider the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 with corresponding norm.
 These are 
\shape italic
spaces of Beppo Levi type
\shape default
 (see 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[4]
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where these spaces would be denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $BL_{m}\left(\tilde{H}^{s}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $BL_{m}^{.}\left(\tilde{H}^{s}\right)$
\end_inset

 respectively): since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is a Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 is a Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is a semi-Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Existence-and-uniqueness"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 In fact, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}\subset\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and a distribution whose derivatives are tempered is tempered, we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}\subset\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 , hence 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}/P_{m-1}\subset\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 and the closed graph theorem shows that this inclusion is continuous.
 So
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is even a semi-Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{I}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now come to comparing 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula $H^{m+s}$
\end_inset

 .
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 bounded we have :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}\right)\left(\Omega\right)=H^{m+s}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $-m-\frac{n}{2}<s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first prove that any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in H^{m+s}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 extends to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 extends to some 
\begin_inset Formula $Pu\in H^{m+s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 with compact support.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Pu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 and we can easily see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left|\tau\right|^{2s}\left|\tau^{\alpha}\hat{Pu}(\tau)\right|^{2}d\tau<\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\alpha\right|=m$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau^{\alpha}\right|^{2}\leq\left|\tau\right|^{2m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{2m+2s}$
\end_inset

 is locally summble (since 
\begin_inset Formula $2m+2s>-n$
\end_inset

) ,and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tau\right|^{2m+2s}\leq2\left(1+\left|\tau\right|^{2}\right)^{m+s}$
\end_inset

 outside some ball.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{m+s}\left(\Omega\right)\subset\left(D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}\right)\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}\left(\Omega\right)\subset D^{-m}\left(\tilde{H^{s}}\right)\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

, with obvious meaning; on the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}^{s}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is always contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{s}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s<\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

; and it is known that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}(H^{s}\left(\Omega\right))=H^{m+s}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\subset H_{loc}^{m+s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})/P_{m-1}\subset H_{loc}^{m+s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

, and the closed graph theorem tells us this inclusion is continuous.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
is a (dense) semi-Hilbert subspace of
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{loc}^{m+s}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another point is that, on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}\right)(\Omega)/P_{m-1}\subset H^{m+s}(\Omega)/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

, the two Hilbert structures are equivalent (both of them are Hilbert subspaces
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{D}^{\prime}\left(\Omega\right)/P_{m-1}$
\end_inset

, so apply the closed graph theorem).
 From this one can easily deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\bar{\Omega}}^{-m-s}\left(\mathbb{R}^{n}\right)\cap P_{m-1}^{o}$
\end_inset

, the dual of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{m+s}\left(\Omega\right)/P_{m-1}^{o}$
\end_inset

, is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D^{-m}\tilde{H}^{s}/P_{m-1}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Existence and uniqueness
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Existence-and-uniqueness"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with stating an abstract frame: let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a locally convex topological vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 its dual, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 a finite-dimensional (for simplicity) subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{o}$
\end_inset

 its orthogonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{o}$
\end_inset

 is naturally identified with the dual space of 
\begin_inset Formula $E/N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A linear subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is called a semi-Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with nullspace 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equipped with a semi-norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert .\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 (with nullspace 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

) deriving from a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-inner product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (nonnegative bilinear form) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left(.,.\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X/N$
\end_inset

 equipped with the natural norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert x+N\right\Vert =\left\Vert x\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 is a Hilbert space, and inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $X/N\curvearrowleft E/N$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $X/N$
\end_inset

 is a Hilbert subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $E/N$
\end_inset

 in the sense of 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SCHWARTZ [IO]
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $X/N$
\end_inset

 has a (unique) reproducing kernel in 
\begin_inset Formula $E/N$
\end_inset

, which is a linear mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $(E/N)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $X/N$
\end_inset

, satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left(y,x\right)\right)=\left\langle e^{\prime},x+N\right\rangle ,\forall x\in X,\forall y\in Le^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 To be slightly simpler, we will say that a linear mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta:N^{o}\rightarrow E$
\end_inset

 is reproducing kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta e^{\prime}\in Le^{\prime}\forall e^{\prime}\in N^{o}\simeq(E/N)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{o}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a reproducing kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left(\theta e^{\prime},x\right)\right)=\left\langle e^{\prime},x\right\rangle ,\forall x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Semi-Hilbert spaces and reproducing kernels provide a simple and convenient
 language for splines.
 However, following theorems 2.1.
 and 2.2.
 could be easily deduced from 
